05852nam a22007455i 9780231850919DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20162015nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013966071  a(OCoLC)1029834534  a(OCoLC)1032695912  a(OCoLC)1037973561  a(OCoLC)1041981722  a(OCoLC)1046606773  a(OCoLC)1046721777  a(OCoLC)1046998058  a97802318509197 a10.7312/baye174222doi  a(DE-B1597)460990  a(OCoLC)931853365  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPER0040302bisacsh  aAP 526002rvk0(DE-625)rvk/7717:00aHolocaust Cinema in the Twenty-First Century :bImages, Memory, and the Ethics of Representation /ced. by Gerd Bayer Bayer, Oleksandr Kobrynskyy Kobrynskyy.  aPilot project. eBook available to selected US libraries only 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2016] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (200 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIntroduction. The Next Chapter in the History of Holocaust Cinema -- tPart One. The past and its presence -- t1. Transformations of Holocaust Memory -- t2. Supplementing Shoah -- t3. The Act of Digging -- t4. The Willing Amnesia -- t5. Wilhelm Brasse’s Photographs from Auschwitz -- tPart two. The ethics of memory -- t6. The Singular Jew -- t7. Locked doors and Hidden Graves -- t8. The Ethics of Perspective and the Holocaust Archive -- tPart three. The legacy of evil -- t9. ‘The doctor is different’ -- t10. On the Cinematic Nazi -- t11. The Holocaust as Case Study -- t12. TV as a Historical Archive? -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the first fifteen years of the twenty-first century, a large number of films were produced in Europe, Israel, the United States, and elsewhere addressing the historical reality and the legacy of the Holocaust. Contemporary Holocaust cinema exists at the intersection of national cultural traditions, aesthetic conventions, and the inner logic of popular forms of entertainment. It also reacts to developments in both fiction and documentary films following the innovations of a postmodern aesthetic. With the number of witnesses to the atrocities of Nazi Germany dwindling, medialized representations of the Holocaust take on greater cultural significance. At the same time, visual responses to the task of keeping memories alive have to readjust their value systems and reconsider their artistic choices.Both established directors and a new generation of filmmakers have tackled the ethically difficult task of finding a visual language to represent the past that is also relatable to viewers. Both geographical and spatial principles of Holocaust memory are frequently addressed in original ways. Another development concentrates on perpetrator figures, adding questions related to guilt and memory. Covering such diverse topics, this volume brings together scholars from cultural studies, literary studies, and film studies. Their analyses of twenty-first-century Holocaust films venture across national and linguistic boundaries and make visible various formal and intertextual relationships within the substantial body of Holocaust cinema.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCollective memory and motion pictures. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945), in motion pictures. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh1 aAssmann, Aleida, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBayer, Gerd Bayer, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBayer, Gerd, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEbbrecht-Hartmann, Tobias, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGershenson